1
00:00:03,530 --> 00:00:06,241
Both victims work
for ZBZ Security.

2
00:00:06,592 --> 00:00:08,014
Company has a contract

3
00:00:08,017 --> 00:00:12,019
with the Turtle Bay Historical
Society right next door.

4
00:00:12,021 --> 00:00:14,238
Now, nothing's missing
from the museum.

5
00:00:14,240 --> 00:00:15,656
We're canvassing
the area

6
00:00:15,658 --> 00:00:18,525
for the gun, shooter,
any possible witnesses.

7
00:00:18,527 --> 00:00:21,078
So, thoughts?

8
00:00:22,313 --> 00:00:24,615
Holmes?
Thoughts?

9
00:00:24,617 --> 00:00:25,616
Sorry, sorry.

10
00:00:25,618 --> 00:00:27,651
I was waiting
for Miss Watson.

11
00:00:27,653 --> 00:00:29,620
I'm training her to analyze
every environment

12
00:00:29,622 --> 00:00:31,872
with the keen eye
of the true detective.

13
00:00:32,957 --> 00:00:34,425
Watson, thoughts?

14
00:00:34,427 --> 00:00:38,178
Um, um...

15
00:00:38,180 --> 00:00:42,999
Looks like both men have been
shot in the chest one time.

16
00:00:43,001 --> 00:00:46,470
Judging from the scuff marks
on the concrete,

17
00:00:46,472 --> 00:00:48,806
looks like they chased
the suspect up here,

18
00:00:48,808 --> 00:00:52,059
who then fired twice
and then ran.

19
00:00:53,778 --> 00:00:56,563
It's tough to say where he went.

20
00:00:56,565 --> 00:00:59,066
The reason it's difficult
to say where he ran

21
00:00:59,068 --> 00:01:01,151
is that no one ran
anywhere at all.

22
00:01:02,120 --> 00:01:04,321
Here we have
two deceased gentlemen,

23
00:01:04,323 --> 00:01:06,657
both of them wearing
the uniform of ZBZ.

24
00:01:06,659 --> 00:01:08,242
Or so it would appear.

25
00:01:08,244 --> 00:01:11,027
This man's patches were
recently sewn on,

26
00:01:11,029 --> 00:01:12,880
and his clothes are
store-bought,

27
00:01:12,882 --> 00:01:15,165
not made by
a uniform company.

28
00:01:15,167 --> 00:01:17,534
So he was posing as a guard.

29
00:01:17,536 --> 00:01:19,703
Nothing is missing
from the museum,

30
00:01:19,705 --> 00:01:22,756
so we assume that he was looking
for access to the parking lot.

31
00:01:22,758 --> 00:01:24,391
It's easy to rifle
through the cars

32
00:01:24,393 --> 00:01:26,477
if you look like you work
for the security firm.

33
00:01:26,479 --> 00:01:27,978
Now, what was in
his pockets? Pockets?

34
00:01:27,980 --> 00:01:29,980
Pockets.

35
00:01:37,572 --> 00:01:40,190
Yeah, see, you thought
he was a victim,

36
00:01:40,192 --> 00:01:42,109
so you were looking
for identification.

37
00:01:42,111 --> 00:01:44,828
But here we have
one, two, three, four

38
00:01:44,830 --> 00:01:46,229
car registration cards.

39
00:01:46,231 --> 00:01:48,165
Each one has
the owner's address on it.

40
00:01:48,167 --> 00:01:49,733
See the game?

41
00:01:49,735 --> 00:01:52,903
Pick an expensive car,
then you call an associate,

42
00:01:52,905 --> 00:01:55,238
who burgles the home
of its owner while they're out.

43
00:01:55,240 --> 00:01:57,407
This man is
a real security guard.

44
00:01:57,409 --> 00:02:00,377
He saw this fellow
lurking around, followed him.

45
00:02:00,379 --> 00:02:02,012
Bad man shoots good man.

46
00:02:02,014 --> 00:02:03,597
Good man, while still alive,

47
00:02:03,599 --> 00:02:06,633
wrests control of gun
from bad man, fires one shot.

48
00:02:06,635 --> 00:02:08,302
Here we are.

49
00:02:08,304 --> 00:02:09,803
One more thing.

50
00:02:09,805 --> 00:02:11,271
His cell phone.

51
00:02:11,273 --> 00:02:13,724
You're gonna check
the last number he dialed;

52
00:02:13,726 --> 00:02:15,025
that's his partner.

53
00:02:15,027 --> 00:02:17,194
He's probably robbing
a place right now.

54
00:02:19,614 --> 00:02:21,615
Would you like to talk
to the burglar?

55
00:02:21,617 --> 00:02:25,285
According to this,
his name is Loco Maurice.

56
00:02:25,287 --> 00:02:28,989
You mustn't allow your failure
to discourage you.

57
00:02:28,991 --> 00:02:31,992
(sighs) Didn't fail.
Not discouraged.

58
00:02:31,994 --> 00:02:34,545
You didn't solve the case,
but you did notice

59
00:02:34,547 --> 00:02:36,279
the incongruity
of the scuff marks.

60
00:02:36,281 --> 00:02:37,664
The next step is learning

61
00:02:37,666 --> 00:02:39,883
to extrapolate your way
to the truth.

62
00:02:39,885 --> 00:02:41,668
Detection is not just
a skill, Watson.

63
00:02:41,670 --> 00:02:43,253
It's a point of view.

64
00:02:43,255 --> 00:02:44,922
You must train yourself
to be alert

65
00:02:44,924 --> 00:02:46,423
to the bizarre,
the unusual,

66
00:02:46,425 --> 00:02:50,177
that which has no place
in any given picture.

67
00:02:50,179 --> 00:02:51,512
Like that stretch limo

68
00:02:51,514 --> 00:02:53,514
with the driver staring
straight at us?

69
00:02:53,516 --> 00:02:54,565
MAN:
Sherlock Holmes?

70
00:02:54,567 --> 00:02:56,299
My name's Crabtree.

71
00:02:56,301 --> 00:02:58,852
We got your name from
a Mr. Musgrave in London.

72
00:02:58,854 --> 00:03:01,271
Local police told us
we'd find you here.

73
00:03:01,273 --> 00:03:03,323
Oh. You say "we."

74
00:03:03,325 --> 00:03:05,141
All I see is a you.

75
00:03:05,143 --> 00:03:07,194
I'm a driver and attaché

76
00:03:07,196 --> 00:03:09,079
for Mr. Gerald Lydon
of Lydon Industries.

77
00:03:09,081 --> 00:03:10,664
You know the company?

78
00:03:10,666 --> 00:03:12,032
You make everything
from Scotch Tape

79
00:03:12,034 --> 00:03:13,667
to diamond-tipped drill bits.

80
00:03:13,669 --> 00:03:16,286
Well, we have all the tape
and drill bits that we need.

81
00:03:16,288 --> 00:03:17,621
Thank you very much.

82
00:03:17,623 --> 00:03:19,706
Mr. Lydon has a proposal
for you.

83
00:03:23,261 --> 00:03:26,129
I sit before you a lucid man.

84
00:03:26,131 --> 00:03:28,098
Vital, I might say.

85
00:03:28,100 --> 00:03:30,851
I hold 18 patents

86
00:03:30,853 --> 00:03:33,670
and I can do 11 pull-ups
at age 58.

87
00:03:33,672 --> 00:03:36,557
And I own exactly
16 forks.

88
00:03:36,559 --> 00:03:38,174
I'm not entirely sure

89
00:03:38,176 --> 00:03:40,027
what we're supposed
to be comparing.

90
00:03:40,029 --> 00:03:44,314
Well, the point, Mr. Holmes,
is that in my good moments,

91
00:03:44,316 --> 00:03:46,400
I'm every bit
the man I was.

92
00:03:46,402 --> 00:03:48,652
But there are fewer
and fewer of those

93
00:03:48,654 --> 00:03:50,037
because I have dementia.

94
00:03:50,039 --> 00:03:51,822
And it's getting worse,

95
00:03:51,824 --> 00:03:55,025
which is why Ms. Tompkins
is following me around.

96
00:03:55,027 --> 00:03:56,877
You have my
condolences.

97
00:03:56,879 --> 00:03:59,079
I don't want your condolences.

98
00:03:59,081 --> 00:04:01,164
I want your help.

99
00:04:01,166 --> 00:04:03,033
Have you ever heard

100
00:04:03,035 --> 00:04:05,869
of hereditary cerebral
amyloid angiopathy?

101
00:04:05,871 --> 00:04:07,804
Hereditary CAA.

102
00:04:07,806 --> 00:04:09,840
It's a genetic disorder.

103
00:04:09,842 --> 00:04:12,342
Less than 20,000
cases recorded.

104
00:04:12,344 --> 00:04:13,894
Dementia is one

105
00:04:13,896 --> 00:04:15,312
of the early symptoms.

106
00:04:15,314 --> 00:04:16,930
And death is the final symptom.

107
00:04:16,932 --> 00:04:20,317
And when it comes to me,
it will complete my murder,

108
00:04:20,319 --> 00:04:24,054
because somebody did this to me,
and I need you to find out who.

109
00:04:24,056 --> 00:04:27,357
So, it's a hereditary disorder.

110
00:04:27,359 --> 00:04:29,526
You have to be born with it.

111
00:04:29,528 --> 00:04:32,613
And there's no history
of it in my family.

112
00:04:32,615 --> 00:04:35,282
They can do a lot of things
in labs now, you know.

113
00:04:35,284 --> 00:04:37,417
And I've consulted with
some of the top geneticists,

114
00:04:37,419 --> 00:04:39,119
and they tell me
that it's possible

115
00:04:39,121 --> 00:04:41,088
that somebody gave me
this disease,

116
00:04:41,090 --> 00:04:42,756
because they want me
out of power!

117
00:04:42,758 --> 00:04:45,125
With all due respect,

118
00:04:45,127 --> 00:04:47,577
maybe these
geneticists are right.

119
00:04:47,579 --> 00:04:50,797
"Possible" does
not mean "likely".

120
00:04:50,799 --> 00:04:53,750
It just means it's
not impossible.

121
00:04:53,752 --> 00:04:56,753
That's what my family says,
that's what the police say,

122
00:04:56,755 --> 00:04:59,556
that I'm paranoid,
that I'm delusional.

123
00:04:59,558 --> 00:05:02,258
I hate to say this, but those
are also symptoms of CAA.

124
00:05:02,260 --> 00:05:05,612
Look, they tell me
that you're the best.

125
00:05:05,614 --> 00:05:08,949
Mr. Holmes, what will it cost
to buy you over to my side?

126
00:05:08,951 --> 00:05:13,153
I only take cases when I believe
I'm acting in good faith.

127
00:05:13,155 --> 00:05:16,623
Now, since I think that
naturally occurring dementia

128
00:05:16,625 --> 00:05:19,626
is by far and away
the most likely explanation

129
00:05:19,628 --> 00:05:23,497
for your plight,
I would not be doing that.

130
00:05:23,499 --> 00:05:26,783
Would you pull over,
please, Crabtree?

131
00:05:26,785 --> 00:05:28,284
I really am
truly sorry.

132
00:05:28,286 --> 00:05:30,887
And I wish you
the best of luck.

133
00:05:47,872 --> 00:05:50,740
(sizzling)

134
00:05:56,197 --> 00:05:58,081
I read the last
stack of books.

135
00:05:58,083 --> 00:06:00,367
No questions... asked.

136
00:06:00,369 --> 00:06:04,371
But, uh, Jeremy Bentham is
a utilitarian philosopher.

137
00:06:04,373 --> 00:06:06,540
That has nothing to do
with being a detective.

138
00:06:06,542 --> 00:06:08,992
Bentham is the father
of modern criminology.

139
00:06:08,994 --> 00:06:11,828
He said that crime is
the result of free will.

140
00:06:11,830 --> 00:06:13,130
(doorbell rings)

141
00:06:13,132 --> 00:06:14,965
Uh, you're gonna put
the acid away

142
00:06:14,967 --> 00:06:16,833
before we answer the door,
right?

143
00:06:21,689 --> 00:06:24,141
Delivery for you,
Mr. Holmes.

144
00:06:24,143 --> 00:06:26,977
Thank you, Crabtree,
but I'm afraid I...

145
00:06:26,979 --> 00:06:28,645
Oh, my God.

146
00:06:28,647 --> 00:06:30,180
Is that...?

147
00:06:30,182 --> 00:06:32,282
A bee in a box?
Yes, it is.

148
00:06:32,284 --> 00:06:34,868
Fairly unimpressive
as far as bribes go.

149
00:06:34,870 --> 00:06:38,405
Not if you're
an apiculturist.

150
00:06:38,407 --> 00:06:42,743
That's an osmia avoseta--
solitary bee

151
00:06:42,745 --> 00:06:45,862
famed for building exquisite
nests from flower petals.

152
00:06:47,665 --> 00:06:50,200
It's on the verge
of extinction.

153
00:06:50,202 --> 00:06:53,369
Crabtree, this is exquisite.

154
00:06:53,371 --> 00:06:54,721
I cannot accept it.

155
00:06:54,723 --> 00:06:57,557
Please tell Mr. Lydon
not to contact me again.

156
00:06:57,559 --> 00:07:00,010
I told him you are a man
of convictions.

157
00:07:00,012 --> 00:07:02,596
Perhaps now
he'll believe me.

158
00:07:14,325 --> 00:07:16,743
This is ridiculous.
Single stick is <i>your</i> hobby.

159
00:07:16,745 --> 00:07:18,561
It's not gonna help me
solve crimes.

160
00:07:18,563 --> 00:07:19,996
(phone ringing)

161
00:07:19,998 --> 00:07:21,782
Aim for the pate.

162
00:07:21,784 --> 00:07:23,399
Good morning, Captain.

163
00:07:23,401 --> 00:07:25,869
GREGSON: Are you in bed with
a guy named Gerald Lydon?

164
00:07:25,871 --> 00:07:27,504
He tried to hire me.
I declined.

165
00:07:27,506 --> 00:07:29,089
Well, that's not what he thinks.

166
00:07:29,091 --> 00:07:31,258
You should get down here.
He's asking for you.

167
00:07:31,260 --> 00:07:32,709
Why?

168
00:07:32,711 --> 00:07:35,545
I don't know,
but we just arrested him.

169
00:07:35,547 --> 00:07:39,132
He shot his driver--
guy named Crabtree.

170
00:07:39,134 --> 00:07:42,035
He's being charged with murder.

171
00:07:42,829 --> 00:07:46,829
